The first commercial integral fast breeder reactor (IFBR) was the Integral Fast Reactor (IFR), designed and built by the Argonne National Laboratory (ANL) for the US Department of Energy's (DOE's) Office of Nuclear Physics. Crystalline graphite, used as neutron moderating material in original designs, was replaced with carbon dioxide (CO2), which eliminates the possibility of a meltdown. The CO2 captures free neutrons instead of absorbing them like regular water does, which makes it a preferable choice for use in a closed fuel cycle. The reactor uses liquid sodium as a coolant and absorber of excess heat, thus eliminating the need for a separate system of pumps and dry storage containers for spent fuel.
